# Characters

Wave characters — coordinates in 4D space, not ASCII, not Unicode.


## Dimensions

ACTIVE DESIGN (v2, from briefing-char-encoding / char-encoding-v2):

  τ: duration    (+1=sustained, 0=transitional, -1=transient)
  χ: place       (+1=front/labial, 0=central/alveolar, -1=back/velar)
  μ: manner      (+1=open vowel, 0=fricative, -1=stop/nasal)
  φ: voicing     (+1=voiced, -1=voiceless)

NOTE: design doc v1 had τ=case. v2 changes τ to duration for consistency
across character/word/architecture levels. Case drops from coordinates
entirely — 'A'='a' at shell 1. Case = walk-level or shell 2 metadata.


## Wave Byte Encoding

  bits [7:6]=τ  [5:4]=χ  [3:2]=μ  [1:0]=φ
  00=0  01=+1  10=extended  11=-1

Shell 1: 1 byte. Shell 2: 1 + N extension bytes.
On ternary hardware: fixed-width 4 trits, no shell distinction.


## Key Properties

  'a' = (+1,+1,+1,+1) = hylo = simplest vocalization
  silence = (0,0,0,0) = wave = identity

  is_letter  = μ ≠ 0
  is_vowel   = μ == +1
  is_stop    = μ == -1 AND τ == -1
  is_nasal   = μ == -1 AND τ == +1
  is_voiced  = φ > 0
  voice_flip = XOR 0x02
  stop↔nasal = XOR 0x80 (τ flip)


## v2 Collision Resolution

v1 collisions fixed: b≠m, d≠n, a≠w, l≠z (all separated by τ=duration).
Remaining collisions are genuinely phonetically identical — separated
at shell 2. Discrimination doubled: ~18→~36 effective regions.

Specific shell-1 collision pairs (all phonetically justified):
  l=r (alveolar approximants), k=c=q=x (4 English letters for /k/),
  g=j (back voiced stops), sh=h (back voiceless fricatives),
  f=th (front voiceless fricatives), v=dh (front voiced fricatives),
  a=i (front open voiced), o=u (back open voiced).


## Cross-Language

Every language fits within shell 2. Shell 3 (7^4=2401) covers all IPA
+ CJK syllable blocks. Tone encoding at shell 2 via τ magnitude.

60% of scripts have no case. The encoding shouldn't penalize them for
a feature only 40% use.


## Network Search

Born-indexed + wave byte trigrams = search without download. Legacy:
download 2MB, parse, scan. Born-indexed: send 9 wave bytes, get ~20
bytes back, sub-millisecond. Character encoding IS the search key format.


## Ternary Dissolves the Tension

Byte inefficiency is x86 tax. On balanced ternary, every coordinate is
4 trits, fixed width. No extension bytes, no shell distinction. The 40%
English overhead goes to zero.


